WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:04.944
Many systems preload every document that might be relevant before the Agent starts.

2
00:00:04.398 --> 00:00:11.742
That can be fast when the corpus is small and stable, but it also spends the attention budget before the Agent knows which detail matters.

3
00:00:11.261 --> 00:00:20.461
Just-in-time retrieval uses lightweight references instead: file paths, stored queries, links, identifiers, folder names, and timestamps.

4
00:00:19.927 --> 00:00:25.425
The Agent keeps the map in context, then opens the specific source when a decision requires it.

5
00:00:24.877 --> 00:00:27.298
This creates progressive disclosure.

6
00:00:26.754 --> 00:00:29.059
A filename suggests purpose.

7
00:00:28.534 --> 00:00:30.782
A directory reveals structure.

8
00:00:30.254 --> 00:00:32.841
A file size suggests complexity.

9
00:00:32.274 --> 00:00:35.108
One search result narrows the next query.

10
00:00:34.529 --> 00:00:40.565
The Agent assembles understanding layer by layer while keeping only the active subset in working context.

11
00:00:40.076 --> 00:00:42.458
Claude Code illustrates the pattern.

12
00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:50.715
Stable project instructions can be loaded up front, while file search, grep, head, and tail let the Agent inspect targeted parts of a large repository.

13
00:00:50.164 --> 00:00:53.710
It does not need every file body in context at once.

14
00:00:53.227 --> 00:00:54.994
The trade-off is real.

15
00:00:54.438 --> 00:01:00.532
Runtime exploration is slower than preloading, and poor navigation can waste tokens on dead ends.

16
00:00:59.984 --> 00:01:06.491
The Agent needs good search tools, informative names, and heuristics for when to stop exploring and act.

17
00:01:06.004 --> 00:01:07.954
Use a hybrid strategy.

18
00:01:07.423 --> 00:01:13.036
Preload stable rules, the current outcome, and the small facts that almost every step needs.

19
00:01:12.514 --> 00:01:17.319
Keep changing, detailed, or rarely used material behind retrieval handles.

20
00:01:16.783 --> 00:01:20.665
The right boundary depends on the task and the cost of a missed detail.

21
00:01:20.186 --> 00:01:24.184
First, keep lightweight references instead of every source body.

22
00:01:23.675 --> 00:01:28.596
Second, let the AI Agent discover detail progressively when it becomes relevant.

23
00:01:28.133 --> 00:01:32.813
Third, balance retrieval focus against the extra time and navigation cost.
